An Introduction to One Sample T-Test.

    Introduction

  • One Sample T-Test is also called Single-Parameter T-Test or Single-Sample T-Test.

  • This test used to determine whether a sample comes from a population with a specific mean.

  • The population mean is not always known, but is theorized.

  • Common use of One Sample t Test:
    • Statistical difference between a mean and a known or hypothesized value of the mean in the population.
    • Statistical difference between a change score and zero.

  • A one-sample t-test is also often used as part of a sampling strategy or to make a comparison to a criterion measure.
  • Sampling Accuracy/Adequacy Example:
    • An education analyst wants to compare the mean math scores of a high school to the national average.

    • Generalized Research Question: Is there a difference in variable of interest between the sample and population?
    • A one-sample t-test would help the analyst determine if this high school score is representative of the population (national average).

  • Comparison to a Criterion Measure Example:
    • Human Resources wants to investigate whether the Research Associates in the School of Medicine are working more than 50 hours per week.

    • Generalized Research Question: Is there a difference in variable of interest and some specific criteria (number)?
    • A one-sample t-test would help Human Resources determine if the Research Associates are working more than the 50 hour per week criteria.


Discuss the Assuptions of a One Sample T-Test.

    What are assumptions?
  • Assumptions are characteristics about a given data.

  • A few examples of statistical assumptions include:
    • Data types: the data has a specific attribute (integer, continuous, categorical, string, boolean).
    • Normality: the data has a normal distribution.
    • Homogenity of variance: the data from multiple groups have the same variance.
    • Linearity: the data has a linear relationship.
    • Independence: the data has a specific attribute.

    Why test for assumptions?
  • Statistical tests are developed making characteristics of the data into consideration

  • Failure to test for these assumptions can result in inaccurate conclusions.

  • Part of the process of using Pearson's Correlation is checking to make sure the data you want to analyze passes the assumptions needed for this test.

  • There are five assumptions that must be met to give you valid results.

  • It is common for data to violate some of these assumptions, and the aim of this section is to discuss how to proceed in those cases.

    The Four Assumptions

  1. One of the dependent variable is continuous data.

  2. The data are Independent and are not correlated/related.

  3. No significant outliers.

  4. Dependent variable should be approximately normally distributed.


One Sample T-Test Hypotheses Statements and Formulas.

  • The null hypothesis \(\boldsymbol{H_{0}} \):
    \[H_{0}: \mu = \mu_{o}\]
  • Where \(\boldsymbol{\mu} \) = sample mean
  • and \(\boldsymbol{\mu_{0}} \) = known or hypothesized population mean.
  • The null hypothesis states that the sample mean is equal to the known or hypothesized population mean.
  • The alternative hypothesis \(\boldsymbol{H_{a}} \):
    \[H_{0}: \mu \neq \mu_{o}\]
  • Where \(\boldsymbol{\mu} \) = sample mean
  • and \(\boldsymbol{\mu_{0}} \) = known or hypothesized population mean.
  • The alternative hypothesis states that the sample mean is not equal to the known or hypothesized population mean.


    • T-Test Formula

      \[t = \frac{\bar X - \mu}{\frac {s}{\sqrt{n}}} \]
    • Where \(\boldsymbol{\bar X} \) = sample mean
    • and \(\boldsymbol{\mu} \) = population mean
    • and \(\boldsymbol{s} \) = sample deviation

State Question and Hypothesis

  • An animal behavioral scientist wants to study hostility in dogs housed in shelters located in low income neighborhoods.

  • The scientist used a method to score hostility, which is as follows:
    • Fearful behavior < 4.0.
    • Normal behavior = 4.0.
    • Hostile behavior > 4.0.

  • The animal behavioral scientist was able to recruit 40 participants in this study, and behavioral scores were recorded.

  • Question: Is the sample representative of the normal population (i.e., is the mean score statistically significantly different from 4.0?)
  • The null hypothesis states that the sample mean is equal to the known or hypothesized population mean.
  • The null hypothesis \(\boldsymbol{H_{0}} \):
    \[H_{0}: \mu = 4.0\]
  • Where \(\boldsymbol{\mu} \) = sample mean
  • and \(\boldsymbol{\mu_{0}} \) = known or hypothesized population mean, 4.0.
  • The alternative hypothesis states that the sample mean is not equal to the known or hypothesized population mean.

  • The alternative hypothesis \(\boldsymbol{H_{a}} \):
    \[H_{0}: \mu \neq 4.0\]
  • Where \(\boldsymbol{\mu} \) = sample mean
  • and \(\boldsymbol{\mu_{0}} \) = known or hypothesized population mean, 4.0.
    State level of significance α
  • is a value in a given hypothesis test for which a P-value less than or equal to is is considered statistically significant.
  • α = 0.05

Step 2: Set up data

    SPSS Variable View
  • Set up variable in variable view.
  • Either import or manually input data.
  • The data is continuous, so the measure is set to Scale

Step 3: Confirm data does not violate assuption 1 (continuous variables) and 2 (instances have paired data)

    SPSS Data View
  • If the study does not meet these two assumptions, then a one-sample t-test is the incorrect statistical test.

  • Assumption 1: Continous data. The hostility score takes any value between 0 - 10, and as a result, it is a continuous data, and met the first assumption.
    Passes Assumption 1

  • Assumption 2: Independence of observations. Each score was obtained from a single dog, a dog was analyzed only once. These conditions make each observation independent of each other.
    Passes Assumption 2

Step 4: Test for significant outliers

  1. Analyze > Explore
  2. Explore Dialogue Box move dependent variable into Dependent List Box.
  3. Click Plots button to open Explore: Plots Dialogue Box
  4. Explore: Plots Dialogue Box Check Normality plots with tests
  5. Explore: Plots Dialogue Box In Descriptive area, uncheck Stem-and-leaf
  6. Click Continue botton.
  7. Retruned to Explore: Plots Dialogue Box and in Display box, click Plots radial dial button.
  8. Click OK
    Inspect BoxPlot
  • Any data points that are more than 1.5 box-lengths from the edge of their box are classified by SPSS Statistics as outliers.
  • SPSS labels extreme data points with circular dots and labeled with a case number (corresponds to the row in the Data View window.
  • Any data points that are more than 3 box-lengths from the edge of their box are classified as extreme points.
  • There are more complicated methods to detect outliers, but this method is the most popular.
  • Conclusion: There were no outliers in the data, as assessed by inspection of a boxplot for values greater than 1.5 box-lengths from the edge of the box.

Step 5: Determine if data is normally distributes by using test for normality.

  • There are various methods that can be used to determine if the data is normally distributed.
  • In this study employs the Shapiro-Wilk test for normality and a Normal Q-Q Plots.
  • Shapiro-Wilk test is recommended if you have a sample size of less than 50 participants.
    Shapiro-Wilk test
  1. Analyze > Descriptive Statistics > Explore
  2. Explore Dialogue Box Move dependent variable to Dependent list
  3. Explore Dialogue Box Click Plots
  4. Explore Plots Dialogue Box click Normality plots with tests
  5. Explore Plots Dialogue Box uncheck Stem-and-leaf check Histogram
  6. Explore Plots Dialogue Box click None in Boxplots area
  7. Click Continue button
  8. Explore Dialogue Box click OK button
    Interpret result
  • Look at the last column in the Shapiro-Wilk section of Test of Normality Output table.

    • If \(\textbf{p-value < 0.05} \) then the results are statistically significant. Data is not normally distributed.

    • If \(\textbf{p-value > 0.05} \) then the results are not statistically significant. Data is normally distributed.

    • The p-value = 0.847; The sig value is greater than the α = 0.05, therefore, the behavioral scores are normally distributed.

  • The behavioral scores were normally distributed, as assessed by Shapiro-Wilk's test (p > .05).

  • If the data was not normally distributed, then there are two options:
    1. Transform data and retest for normality.

    2. Use a nonparametric test
    Testing for normality using Normal Q-Q plots
  • A normal Q-Q plot is a good method to graphically assess for normality.
  • If the data is normally distributed the circular dots that represent the data points for each variable, will be positioned approximately along a diagnoal line in the Normal Q-Q plot.
  • The data will not align perfectly to the line, but will hover around it.
  • By inspected the plots we see that the data points wrap around the line, with minor skewness.
  • Basedon the Normal Q-Q Plots, we can conclude that the engagement scores were normally distributed for the behavioral scores, as assessed by visual inspection of Normal Q-Q Plots..

Step 6: Carry out One-Sample T-Test and Interpret Results.

  1. Analyze > Compare Means > One-Sample T Test
  2. One-Sample T Test dialogue box
  3. Transfer the dependent variable into the Test Variable(s) box
  4. In Test Value area, type in test value 4.0 in our example.
  5. Click on Options button and in One-Sample T Test: Options dialogue box keep conditions as default, click on Continue botton.
  6. Click on Continue botton and then Click on OK button to generate output.
    Interpretations of results: Descriptive Statistics
  • This test will determine if the sample data for behavioral scores in shelters located in low income neighborhoods come from a normal population (4.0, which means normal behaving dogs).
  • Descriptive statistics can be obtained from the One-Sample Statistics table in the output.
  • The Mean behavioral score (3.73 ± 0.74) was lower than the population 'normal' behavioral score of 4.0.
    Interpretations of results: One-Sample Test
  • One-Sample Test Table reports the result of the one-sample t-test.
  • The top row provides the value of the known or hypothesized population mean that is compared to the sample data.
  • The first three columns provide information on whether the population means are statistically significantly different
  • The t value was obtained using the formula described in an earlier section in thos post.
  • Interpreting statistical significance:
    • If \(\textbf{p-value < 0.05} \) then the results are statistically significant. Data mean is not equal to the population mean.

    • If \(\textbf{p-value > 0.05} \) then the results are not statistically significant. Data mean is equal to the population mean.

    • The p-value = 0.001; The sig value is less than the α = 0.05, therefore, the behavioral scores are significantly different from the population (4.0).

  • Hostility score was statistically significantly lower than the population normal depression score, t(39) = -2.381, p = .022.
